<taxonomy>
    <title>Office of the Historian Subject Taxonomy of the History of U.S. Foreign Relations</title>
    <subtitle>Collection: Topics</subtitle>
    <description>
        <p>The Subject Taxonomy of the History of U.S. Foreign Relations is a hierarchical taxonomy
            that consists of categories and tags. The taxonomy is organized into ___ top-level
            categories: <list>
                <item>Agreements and Mandates</item>
                <item>Events</item>
                <item>Organizations</item>
                <item>People</item>
                <item>Places</item>
                <item>Topics</item>
            </list> Below these top-level categories are additional nested levels of categories and
            tags, becoming more specific at deeper levels.</p>
        <!--
        <p>Each category and tag conforms to the following structure: it must contain an "id" and
            "label", and optionally can contain a "definition" and/or "usage-hint". The "id"
            uniquely identifies a tag in the taxonomy and should be lower-cased and
            hyphen-delimited. The "label" is how the item is displayed to end users. The
            "definition" defines the item and will be displayed to all users. The "usage-hint"
            contains instructions to staff who perform the tagging about how to use. To create a
            definition for a tag, place a "definition" element after an entry's label. To add a
            usage hint for a tag, place a "usage-hint" element after the label (or after the
            "definition" element, if one already exists).</p>
            -->
        <!-- Note: Values for xml:lang attributes were sourced from http://www.iana.org/assignments/language-subtag-registry/language-subtag-registry -->
    </description>

